== The Weiser Concise Guide to Alchemy
_by Brian Cotnoir, edited and introduced by James Wasserman_

#hm-note[
  Cotnoir began his study of alchemy at age seventeen, walking into Samuel Weiser's Bookstore in New York. This book is, in his own words, the guide he wished had existed when he started. The practical procedures are drawn from primary historical sources and standardized against contemporary practitioners including Archibald Cockren, Alexander von Bernus, Augusto Pancaldi, Frater Albertus, Manfred Junius, and Jean Dubuis — all working from the Paracelsian tradition. Cotnoir himself has accomplished parts of the Great Work though not the full Opus Magnum.
]

=== Preface: What is Alchemy?

#doctrine[
  "By finishing what nature had started by separating, purifying, and balancing the three principles and recombining them, lead could be completed and perfected, transmuted into gold."
]

- The central concept in alchemy is *transmutation*: the fundamental change of one thing into another, from a grosser, impure state to a more refined, balanced, and pure state — on multiple levels simultaneously: physically, spiritually, and symbolically.
- In the worldview of alchemy, each thing in creation is a dynamic mix of body, spirit, and soul. A thing's physicality is only one aspect of that thing.
- "Alchemy is much like iconography. An icon can be seen as a window showing the other, inner aspect of one's self. In creating an icon one is simultaneously working on the inner self, the inner icon." Both are *techniques of gnosis* — stages and steps on the ladder of ascent.
- Alchemy in Greek = *chrysopoeia* ("gold-making"), or better: "gold-composing." Making in the sense of *poesis* — composition, as in music. The poet takes words (material) from the dictionary, rules (technique) from grammar, poetic form (process) — and creates. So too the alchemist.
- Alchemy "employs the agency of Nature and imitates her operations." False alchemy "works on erroneous principles and employs the tyrant and the destroyer of Nature for agency." — Pernety, 1758.

#doctrine[
  "Alchemy is a science and art of making a fermentative powder, which transmutes the imperfect metals into gold, and which is a useful universal remedy for all the natural illnesses of man, of animals and of plants." — Antoine-Joseph Pernety, 1758
]

- _"Ora, lege, lege, lege, relege, labora et invenies"_ — "Pray, read, read, read, reread, work, and you shall discover." This is the whole of the method. — Mutus Liber, Altus, 1677.
- Work with living substances. The inner development of the alchemist is one of the fundamental keys to the process.

=== Overview of Alchemy

==== On Reading Alchemical Texts

- "Liber enim librum aperit." — One book opens another. — Rhazes (ar-Razi)
- Terms and materials in one text are defined and scattered throughout several books — concealing knowledge from fools while ensuring a diligent reader could piece it together.
- One alchemist will use "Green Lion" to mean stibnite; another says it is vitriol. In each context, each is correct. *Do not assume a term means the same thing from writer to writer, period to period, or even within a single writer's own works.*
- Methods of concealment: (1) many names for one material; (2) repeating one or two materials camouflaged in varied terms; (3) stating a true fact then immediately denying it ("the mercury is not ordinary mercury but the mercury of the sages" — consider both meanings, as sometimes the confession is correct, and in other texts the denial is correct).
- An excellent method of study: reproduce alchemical images by hand. This forces careful study of composition. Meditate on the meanings as you do so.
- There are as many alchemies as there are alchemists. Context is everything.
- Gold to the alchemists = perfection. Incorruptible; nothing corrodes or harms it save Aqua Regia. Lead = overabundance of impure, raw Mercury, a little Sulphur, and a heavy yet porous Salt — unripe, immature gold.


=== Part One: Theory

==== Chapter 1: The Aspects of Alchemy

#doctrine[
  "Nothing that is has a nature, but only mixing and parting of the mixed, and nature is but a name given them by men." — Empedocles
]

- The word *theory* comes from Greek *theoria* = "contemplation," or more exactly "divine vision." Alchemical theory is a *cosmology* — a system for understanding how elements, events, and phenomena evolve, interact, and dissolve.

===== The Four Elements (Classical Definitions)

*Fire* (Heraclitus; Empedocles: Hades/Typhon; red; Feeling):
- Aquinas: hot and dry. Avicenna: natural position above all other elements in the sublunary region. Matures, rarefies, refines, and intermingles with all things; penetrates Air; subsumes the two heavy cold elements. Expands, rises, moves toward limits. Any highly reactive or catalytic substance is predominantly fire. *Platonic solid: tetrahedron.*

*Air* (Anaximenes; Empedocles: Zeus/Osiris; yellow; Thinking):
- Aquinas: wet and hot. Avicenna: above Water, beneath Fire. Rarefies, renders things finer, lighter, more delicate, softer, better able to move to a higher sphere. Stretches and contracts, expands and rises. Any gas under normal conditions is predominantly Air. *Platonic solid: octahedron.*

*Water* (Thales; Empedocles: Persephone/Nephthys; blue; Intuition):
- Aquinas: cold and wet. Avicenna: surrounds Earth and surrounded by Air. Allows things to be molded, spread out, attempered; easily parts with an old shape and readily accepts a new one. Contracts and falls. Anything liquid is predominantly Water. *Platonic solid: icosahedron.*

*Earth* (Xenophanes; Empedocles: Hera/Isis; green; Solidity/Persistence):
- Aquinas: dry and cold. Avicenna: center of existence — stationary. Earth fixes parts of our body together in compact form — how outward form is maintained. Contracts and falls. Anything solid under normal conditions is predominantly Earth. *Platonic solid: cube.*

*Quintessence (Ether):*
- Has no qualities. It is the field — the source of all matter and the space in which it exists. *Platonic solid: dodecahedron.*

- The order of the elements from the center out: Earth, Water, Air, Fire, and Space.

===== Two Active/Passive Qualities

- *Active qualities (hot/cold):* cause bodies to coalesce (hot) or dissolve (cold).
- *Passive qualities (dry/moist):* determine how bodies respond.
- Each element has two qualities — one primary, one secondary:
  - Fire: Hot (primary), Dry (secondary — all moisture consumed by heat).
  - Air: Wet (primary), Hot (secondary — closeness to Fire).
  - Water: Cold (primary), Wet (secondary — closeness to Air).
  - Earth: Dry (primary — unresolved into humidity; most dense), Cold (secondary — closeness to Water).

===== Rotation of the Elements

- Elements interlinked through sharing one quality. Change one quality → rotation into adjacent element. Earth → Water → Air → Fire (and back). "It is clear that generation of the elements will be circular." — Aristotle
- "Fire lives the death of earth, and air lives the death of fire, water lives the death of air, earth that of water." — Heraclitus, 6th c. B.C.E.
- *Practical alchemical rotations:* Earth to Water = melting/dissolution in water; Water to Air = boiling; Air to Water = distillation; Air to Fire = combustion or calcination.

===== The Two Exhalations (Aristotle — Genesis of Metals)

- A dry "earthy smoke" (small particles of Earth on their way to becoming Fire) and a wet "watery vapor" (small particles of Water on their way to becoming Air). When trapped in the earth: earthy smoke dominates → stones and minerals form; watery vapor dominates → metals form.

===== The Two Principles (Jabir ibn Hayyan)

- The earthy smoke is first converted into *Sulphur*; the watery vapor into *Mercury*. Their combination in various proportions and purity, plus duration of gestation in the earth, gives rise to the variety of metals and minerals.
- Pure Sulphur + Mercury in equilibrium = gold. Impure and imbalanced = lead, iron, copper, tin, silver. The quicksilver is unchanging; the sulphur tinges and gives form or character to the mix. The quality of the earth also plays a part.
- From St. Albertus Magnus (*Libellus de alchimia*): pure red sulphur + quicksilver = gold. Pure white sulphur + quicksilver = silver. Red corrupt burning sulphur + quicksilver = copper. White corrupt sulphur + quicksilver = tin. White corrupt sulphur + quicksilver in foetid earth = iron. Black corrupt sulphur + quicksilver = lead.
- *Transmutation logic:* all metals are composed of the same materials; it is only a question of purifying and balancing the Sulphur and Mercury within the metal to transform it to its highest state — gold.

===== The Three Principles (Paracelsus)

- Paracelsus added *Salt* to Sulphur and Mercury: Three Principles representing Body, Soul, and Spirit.
- Sulphur = volatility (whatever boils, an oil). Mercury = unctuousness (whatever rises as fumes, a liquor). Salt = solidity (what remains in the ashes, an alkali).
- Each thing can be broken down into its Mercury, Sulphur, and Salt — not just metals but all flora and fauna. "There are as many sulphurs, salts, and mercuries as there are objects." — Paracelsus.

===== Materia Prima

- *Materia prima* (prime matter / "hyle"): formless "matter" that precedes actual substantial existence; pure potentiality of being. *Forma substantia* (substantial form): that which gives existence to matter. When they join, the three dimensions and the beginnings of matter arise.
- Paracelsus: "an object can be separated from its matter and continue to exist as a pure form which is transferable to matter." To reduce matter to its prime matter is one of the steps necessary for transmutation.
- Note: in alchemical texts, *materia prima* also sometimes means the actual starting material for a given process — be aware of which meaning is in use.

#hm-note[
  Nuclear verification: In 1919, Sir Ernest Rutherford transformed nitrogen into oxygen (actual elemental transmutation). In the 1970s, the Society of Heavy Ion Research in Darmstadt, Germany removed proton-electron pairs from uranium (92 protons) until 79 remained — uranium transmuted into gold.
]


==== Chapter 2: Cosmology

- The cosmological blueprint of alchemy = the *Ptolemaic system*: Earth at center; Four Elements fall outward; beyond them is the Ether, divided into shells carrying planets. Planets were seen as luminous spots on transparent shells, or holes through which fire from above blasted through. Moving shells created the *"music of the spheres"* (Pythagoras, 580–500 B.C.E.).

===== The Seven Planetary Spheres

*☽ Moon:* Cold and moist; humidifying; causes putrefaction. Feminine. Subconscious. Memory. Realm of Dreams. Body: stomach, breasts, womb, bodily fluids, left side. Metal: Silver. Day: Monday. Zodiac: 4th House, Cancer. Deities: Diana, Artemis, Selene, Khons.

*☿ Mercury:* Cold and dry (masculine) / cold and moist (feminine); androgynous; drying and absorptive. Mind. Communication. Intellect. Body: arms, hands, shoulders, lungs, solar plexus, abdomen, intestines, nervous and respiratory systems. Metal: Quicksilver. Day: Wednesday. Zodiac: 3rd and 6th Houses, Gemini and Virgo. Deities: Mercury, Hermes, Thoth.

*♀ Venus:* Warm and moist; warms moderately but mostly humidifies. Feminine. Affection, love, beauty. Principle of Attraction. Body: neck, kidneys, ovaries, veins and circulation. Metal: Copper. Day: Friday. Zodiac: 2nd and 7th Houses, Taurus and Libra. Deities: Venus, Aphrodite, Isis.

*☉ Sun:* Hot and dry; heating. Masculine. Vitality, ego, individuality. Principle of Fatherhood. Authority. Body: heart, back, spine, spinal cord, right side. Metal: Gold. Day: Sunday. Zodiac: 5th House, Leo. Deities: Sol, Apollo, Helios, Ra.

*♂ Mars:* Hot and dry; dries and burns. Masculine. Energy and drive. Principle of Active Desire. Initiatory, aggressive. Body: head, muscles, sex organs, virility, forcefulness. Metal: Iron. Day: Tuesday. Zodiac: 1st and 8th Houses, Aries and Scorpio. Deities: Mars, Ares, Horus.

*♃ Jupiter:* Warm and moist; heats and humidifies; "produces fertilizing winds." Masculine. Ethics, Moral values, Philosophy. Abstract mind. Principle of Expansion. Body: blood, arteries and circulation, hips, thighs, feet, liver. Metal: Tin. Day: Thursday. Zodiac: 9th and 12th Houses, Sagittarius and Pisces. Deities: Jupiter, Zeus, Ammoun.

*♄ Saturn:* Cold and dry; cools and moderately dries. Masculine. Principle of Contraction and Restriction. Discipline, responsibility. Body: bones, joints, knees, spleen, skin, teeth. Metal: Lead. Day: Saturday. Zodiac: 10th and 11th Houses, Capricorn and Aquarius. Deities: Saturn, Kronos, Nephthys.

- Flow of energy from Saturn down to Earth follows a specific planetary order shown as a seven-pointed star: Saturn → Jupiter → Mars → Sun → Venus → Mercury → Moon → Earth.
- "The energy of the cosmos flows from the Creator through the planets to the sublunary world, each sphere transmitting as well as adding its own imprint as the impulse moves from beyond the fixed stars toward manifestation."
- The Sphere of the Moon = the boundary between the world of change (sublunary) and the realm of unchanging perfection.


