===== Lunar Month

- The Moon rules the Plant Kingdom. Work should ideally follow and move with its phases.
- *New Moon to First Quarter:* Productive of moisture. Seed to sprout — inception and initial growth.
- *First Quarter to Full Moon:* Productive of heat. Sprout to bloom.
- *Full Moon to Last Quarter:* Productive of dryness. Bloom to fruit. Completion and realization; beginning of crystallization and later disintegration.
- *Last Quarter to New Moon:* Productive of cold. Fruit to seeds. Action completed; dormancy or decomposition.
- The alchemical processes symbolized by the Signs of the Zodiac are *strengthened by the presence of the Full Moon* in the respective sign. (Example: Sublimation is boosted by the Full Moon in Libra.)
- The completion of the work should coincide with the Moon's return to the Sun — when the Moon is one minute from the Sun.

===== Planetary Days and Hours

- Days: Sun → Sunday. Moon → Monday. Mars → Tuesday. Mercury → Wednesday. Jupiter → Thursday. Venus → Friday. Saturn → Saturday.
- Each day is divided into 24 hours (12 day, 12 night), each with a planetary ruler. The planet ruling the day rules the *first hour* (hour of sunrise). Subsequent hours follow in order: *Sun, Venus, Mercury, Moon, Saturn, Jupiter, Mars* — then repeating.
- Day and night are divided *evenly by twelve* giving unequal "hours" — a summer daylight "hour" may exceed 60 minutes; a winter one may be as short as 45 minutes. First hour of day = sunrise; first hour of night = sunset. System documented by Cornelius Agrippa (1486–1535).
- Most important: work with a sense of harmony and not slavishly follow the rules. "Poetry involves the following of the rules, but the best poets play with rules to create surprising juxtapositions and beauty." Alchemy brings this sense of a living art to all its operations.


==== Chapter 4: Microcosm — The Body and Its Composition

- The body = microcosm, the reflection of all that is above. The Four Elements expressed in the body as *humors*: Fire → Blood, Air → Yellow Bile, Water → Phlegm, Earth → Black Bile.
- *Four Temperaments:* Blood → Sanguine (happy, optimistic, passionate, fiery). Yellow Bile → Choleric (practical, rational, impatient, angry). Phlegm → Phlegmatic (sensitive, peaceful, soft, brooding, sad). Black Bile → Melancholic (intelligent, cultured, restless, depressive).
- Planetary rulership of body parts (see Chapter 2 Planetary Spheres above for full details).
- Build up and visualize an image of the cosmos with elemental links and planetary interconnections. Imagine this sphere from the outside looking in: Fixed Stars → Saturn → Jupiter → Mars → Sun → Venus → Mercury → Moon → our world of the Four Elements. *Learn it so well you can actually see it. See it so well you can actually move about in it.* Use this diagram as the basis for visualization and contemplation.


==== Chapter 5: Inner Practice

#doctrine[
  "When you make the two one, and when you make the inside like the outside and the outside like the inside, and the above like the below, and when you make the male and the female one and the same... then you will enter the Kingdom." — The Gospel of Thomas
]

- Alchemy is a *technique or path of gnosis* — direct knowledge of God. It is an approach to the divine *through* matter. Our inner light is imprisoned or obscured by material fog; alchemy shows a way of ascent, a return to God through matter itself.
- The material world and the body are not bad and can actually be used as an aid in the *unio mystica*. The body is kept strong and healthy — to have more time and energy to pursue the inner work and to benefit others.
- One thing necessary for inner work: a *steady mind* — strong, supple, focused; able to stay where you place it. Without a steady mind, no real progress can be made.

===== Breath-Counting Practice

#lab[
  - Breathe normally; allow attention to follow the breath out and then in. Count breathing cycles: exhale, inhale = one; up to ten. When you notice you are no longer counting, start over. Continue 3–5 minutes initially, extending over time.
  - In actual meditation the only thing that changes is the *object* — a visualization, an analysis of an object's composition, a recitation, or a review of a process. The technique of holding the mind to the object remains the same.
]

- Alchemists warn about certain knowledge in the hands of evil, greedy people. Secrecy and silence protect the work. Strive to reduce all sources of conflict and disruption around the work and in life in general.
- Nicholas Flamel and his soror mystica Perenelle succeeded in the Great Work three times. By 1413 they had founded 14 Hospitals in Paris, built three Chapels from the ground, and aided many widows and orphans. The beginning of all alchemical action should be dedicated to the alleviation of suffering.


==== Chapter 6: Tabula Smaragdina

- The *Tabula smaragdina* ("The Emerald Tablet") is the very heart of alchemy — considered one of the oldest alchemical texts. Legend: found near Hebron in a cave (the tomb of Hermes/Thoth) by Zara (Sarah, wife of Abraham), or Alexander the Great, or Apollonius of Tyanna. Engraved in Phoenician on a tablet of emerald.
- Earliest documented Arabic text: ~800 A.D. Entered Europe in 12th century via Hugo of Satalla's Latin translation. The 1541 printed version became most widely known.
- "At the very least, a copy of the Tabula smaragdina should be tacked above your workbench and read and contemplated before working. Meditate on it, line by line, word by word, and it will gradually open itself to you as you gain understanding from the actual work."

===== The Emerald Tablet (1541 Latin version — Cotnoir translation)

#doctrine[
  True, without lie, certain and most true.
  That which is below is as that which is above, and that which is above is as that which is below, to accomplish the miracles of the One.
  And as all things came from the One by the contemplation of the One, thus all things arise from this one thing by adaptation.
  Its father is the Sun, its mother is the Moon. The wind carried it in its belly. Its nurse is the earth.
  The Father of every miracle in the whole world is here.
  Its power is complete, if it will be turned into earth.
  You shall separate earth from fire, the subtle from the gross, gently and with great ingenuity.
  It ascends from earth to heaven, and again descends into the earth, and receives the powers of the things above and below. Thus you shall have the glory of the whole world. All obscurity shall fly from you.
  This is the strength of every strength, for it overcomes every subtle thing and shall penetrate every solid thing.
  Thus the world was created.
  From this shall come marvelous adaptations, of which this is the method.
  Therefore I am called Hermes Trismegistus, having the three parts of the philosophy of the whole world.
  It is completed that which I had to say about the operation of the Sun.
]

- The associated emblem (traditionally joined to this text since 1588) shows the VITRIOL acronym in the outer ring: *Visita Interiora Terrae Rectificando Invenies Occultum Lapidem* — "Visit the Interior of the Earth, and by Rectifying you will Find the Hidden Stone."


=== Part Two: Practice

==== Chapter 7: The Basics of Alchemy

#doctrine[
  "Nature must serve as the basis and model of science, and Art must work according to Nature as far as possible, therefore, the Artist must observe Nature and operate how she operates." — St. Albertus Magnus
]

- All raw materials should be considered as *living* and worked with clear intent. Think of the difference between a meal prepared with fresh ingredients vs. one prepared with frozen or stale components.
- One can use chemical equivalents (e.g. diluted acetic acid instead of distilled red wine vinegar) to practice and study the *techniques* of alchemy without wasting precious material — like doing a color study for a larger painting while saving the lapis lazuli for the actual painting. But recognize that this is not alchemy.

===== Jabir ibn Hayyan's Four Basic Techniques

1. *Purification* — separation of impure from pure; by fire (calcination / sublimation) or by water (distillation / filtration).
2. *Solution* — through maceration and dissolution.
3. *Coagulation* — by crystallization, congelation, or evaporation.
4. *Combination* — achieved by circulation, cohobation, digestion, crystallization, or fixation.

===== Glossary of Alchemical Operations

- *Calcination:* Burning anything to ashes — burning off all combustible impurities. Can also mean melting a metal in the presence of air while stirring, oxidizing it and forming a calx.
- *Circulation:* Gentle heating of a solution and cooling of its vapors. Condensation flows back into the original solution. The solution rotates from liquid to vapor to liquid continuously.
- *Cohobation:* Taking a distillate and pouring it back over whatever remains of the material from which it was distilled.
- *Congelation:* Turning a liquid into a solid. Can also mean solidification of a mass due to loss of water or solvent; or crystallization.
- *Crystallization:* Opening of a body or congealing of a liquid around solid matter. Also used to purify salt.
- *Digestion:* Slow, gentle "cooking." Mixture placed in a sealed flask, put in a warm dark place, kept at around *40°C*.
- *Dissolution:* Dissolving one substance (solute) into a liquid (solvent).
- *Distillation:* Extraction of a liquor from a body or solution by heating, cooling, condensing the vapor, and collecting the resulting liquid.
- *Evaporation:* Removal of the more volatile portions of a mixture by exposing it to the atmosphere; sometimes by gentle heating.
- *Fermentation:* Breaking down of the plant and release of its Mercury (alcohol) with the aid of a ferment or yeast. A similar process occurs in the mineral kingdom.
- *Filtration:* Mechanical separation of particulate matter from a liquid; through filter papers, fritted glass, screens, and funnels.
- *Fixation:* Making that which is volatile non-volatile. Varies from material to material.
- *Maceration:* A form of dissolution — soaking herbs in water or alcohol. Takes ~2–3 days in water (too short = not all virtues extracted; too long = decomposition may start). With alcohol: no real time limit.
- *Multiplication:* A process in the Great Work where the strength of the Philosopher's Stone is augmented.
- *Projection:* A process in the Great Work where the Philosopher's Stone is tested by changing lead or mercury into gold or silver.
- *Putrefaction:* Decomposition of the impurities of the body, the ephemeral parts. A form of purification, preparation for the opening of the body.
- *Sublimation:* Purification of certain salts that, when heated sufficiently, change from solid to gas and back to solid without going through the liquid phase. Sal ammoniac is the exemplary case.

===== Four Degrees of Fire

- *First Degree — Balneum vaporis (steam bath):* flask heated by suspending it over steam. Also *Balneum marie* (Maria's Bath / water bath) — flask immersed in tepid or boiling water up to the height of the material.
- *Second Degree — Ash bath:* pot of ashes heated; flask immersed up to the height of its material — hotter than boiling water.
- *Third Degree — Sand (or iron dust) bath:* same as ash bath but uses sand or iron dust — hotter still.
- *Fourth Degree — Bare flame / reverberating flame:* hottest achievable. Traditionally a charcoal fire in the *athanor* (Arabic *al-tannur*: oven) — a simple brick or clay furnace shaped like a tower. Today: electric hotplates, gas burners. "The athanor is the centerpiece of the alchemical laboratory, comparable to the heart and hearth of a home."

===== Alchemical Vessels (Historical)

- *Alembic:* The head/cap of a still that condenses vapor into liquid.
- *Curcurbite:* The lower part of the still holding the liquid to be distilled.
- *Retort:* A single distillation vessel with a built-in bent tube.
- *Aludel:* Oval-shaped flask open at both ends, placed between curcurbite and alembic to expand vapors and further separate the more volatile from the less volatile.
- *Pelican:* Circulatory vessel with two side tubes that feed condensed vapors back into the body.

===== Eight Prerequisites from St. Albertus Magnus (*Libellus de Alchimia*)

1. *Silence:* "The worker in this art must be silent and secretive. The secret will be lost and the work remain imperfect."
2. *Place:* "Should have a place and a special house, hidden from men."
3. *Time:* "Observe the time in which the work must be done." (Sublimations are of little value in winter.)
4. *Perseverance:* "Be careful and assiduous... if he begins and does not persevere, he will lose both materials and time."
5. *Right Use:* "It should be done according to the usage of art."
6. *Glass:* "All vessels in which medicines may be put... should be of glass or glazed."
7. *Caution:* "Be on one's guard before all else against associating oneself with princes or potentates." If unsuccessful, you will suffer; if successful, you will be detained, "ensnared by your own words and caught by your own discourses."
8. *Funding:* "No one should begin operations without plenty of funds" to complete the work — with the work incomplete, time, material, everything has been wasted.


==== Chapter 8: The Preparatory Work

#doctrine[
  "Where Nature ends, there the Art of man begins, for Nature's ultimate matter is man's primal matter." — Paracelsus
]

===== Water

- All water should be distilled before use unless otherwise noted.
- Water may be collected from springs, rain, snow, or dew. *Dew* (especially spring dew) and *rain during thunderstorms* are particularly valued for the amount of "fire" they hold (lightning fixes nitrogen, increasing the charge of celestial fire).
- To collect thunderstorm rain: place *nonmetal* buckets outside during the storm. Filter. Save some undistilled for future use; distill the rest. Store in glass bottles.

===== The Grapevine (Root of Alchemy)

- Without wine, vinegar, and Salt of Tartar — all obtained from the grapevine — there would be no alchemy. They are also the best materials for practicing fermentation and calcination.

===== Making Wine

#lab[
  - Press juice from grapes (or macerate plants in water for 2 days). Temperature: 27°C. Add sugar if desired; add yeast.
  - Maintain temperature between 21°C and 24°C; keep below 29.5°C. Stir twice daily.
  - When violent fermentation stops, draw off liquid; press pulp. Keep ~15% separate for topping up. Add fermentation lock.
  - After 3 weeks, draw off wine from sediment and top up. For maximum alcohol, repeat 2 more times with 3-month intervals, then a final 6-month fermentation. Wine = typically ~12% alcohol.
  - Distill to obtain Spirit of Wine (Mercury), or use to make vinegar.
]

===== Making Vinegar

#lab[
  - Dilute wine to 5–7% alcohol. Pour 3 parts wine into a sanitized glass or stoneware container, filling less than 2/3 full. Add 1 part vinegar culture with active bacteria.
  - Store in a dark place at 27–29.5°C. A film (the "mother") will form on top. At 24–27°C, conversion takes ~6–8 weeks.
  - Add new wine below the "mother" every 4–8 weeks. When all alcohol is converted, draw off the vinegar; pasteurize and filter. Vinegar = 5% acetic acid.
  - To decolor red wine vinegar: add 50 g bone charcoal per liter; stir often; in several days the color is absorbed, leaving the vinegar clear.
]

===== Salt of Tartar (Potassium Carbonate, K₂CO₃)

#lab[
  - Also called potash or pearl ash. The most common salt in land plants. Obtained from dried grapevine, oak wood, or best of all from raw tartar (wine stone from wine barrels).
  - *Calcine* the material to ash. Mix ash with distilled rainwater; heat and stir to dissolve (*leaching*). Filter. *Evaporate* (do not allow to boil). Collect damp salts; calcine again. Redissolve in hot water, filter, evaporate. Repeat until all salts are pure.
  - Final calcination drives off all excess water. Result: very white or bluish salt. This is the Salt of Tartar.
  - *Highly hygroscopic* (absorbs water from air). Store in an *airtight, moisture-proof container*. *Salt of Tartar attacks glass* — use glazed ceramic containers. This same leaching process can be used on any plant to obtain its salt.
]


==== Chapter 9: The Art of Distillation

===== Spirit of Wine

#lab[
  - Take red wine; use *electric heat* (never open flame when distilling flammables). Distill over the spirit (alcohol).
  - *Discard all liquid that distills under 76°C* — this eliminates methanol (bp 64°C, very poisonous) which does not blend with ethanol and is therefore separable.
  - First distillation at ~80°C yields 50–60% alcohol (*aqua vitae* of Villanova, ~1300 A.D.; useful for herbal tinctures).
  - Subsequent distillations at 78.5°C (boiling point of ethanol) yield the sharp Spirit of Wine. *Maximum achievable concentration: ~95%* due to the hygroscopic nature of alcohol.
]

===== Rectified Spirit of Wine

#lab[
  - To remove the last water: take Spirit of Wine + calcined Salt of Tartar (calcined at 350°C for at least 1 hour to dry it — this enables it to absorb remaining water).
  - *Ratio 1:* 1 part calcined Salt of Tartar : 4 parts Spirit of Wine. Macerate 1 day; shake occasionally; keep closed. Distill → Rectified Spirit of Wine.
  - *Ratio 2 (higher concentration):* 1 part calcined tartar : 6 parts Spirit of Wine, followed by a further distillation over 25 g calcined tartar per 1000 ml. With moisture traps, concentration can reach 99.5%. Use *immediately* — extremely hygroscopic at this purity.
]

===== Distilled Vinegar

#lab[
  - Acetic acid boils at 118°C; water at 100°C. Three fractions:
    - ~100°C: mostly water.
    - 103°C peaking at 105°C: water + some acetic acid. Save separately.
    - Switch receivers at ~105°C. 105–118°C: mostly acetic acid. Distill carefully.
  - *Do not burn; do not distill to dryness* — stop when residue has consistency of honey.
  - Can re-distill to reach up to 80% acetic acid. For most metalwork, 20–30% is sufficient. Determine concentration with a hydrometer.
  - *Practical note:* 5% vinegar → 80% acetic acid requires starting with 16 liters of red wine vinegar (almost 4 gallons, 95% of it water).

  *Freeze-concentration (before distillation):*
  - Fill a bottle halfway with red wine vinegar; lay on its side. Let freeze (freezes at -3°C). Tip upside down into a collection flask — acetic acid melts first (mp 16.7°C) and runs off red. Collect in fractions until the block of ice is white and colorless (only water remains). Discard ice. Repeat freeze-and-drain cycles until volume is manageable for distillation.
]


==== Chapter 10: The Purification of Salts — Calcination, Crystallization, and Sublimation

===== Crystallization

#lab[
  - Dissolve salt in distilled water at 45–50°C to make a saturated solution. Let sit 1 hour; decant into another flask; keep heating. When small crystals begin to form, remove from heat and cool.
  - *To grow large crystals:* Pour prepared solution ~3 cm deep in a beaker. Cover loosely with foil or paper towel. Once crystals grow to 2–5 cm, add more solution as needed. Once at desired size, decant solution back into stock. Select best-looking crystals; put each in its own beaker with 3 cm of solution. Turn crystal once daily. If others start to form, decant them back to stock.
]

===== Sublimation of Sal Ammoniac

#lab[
  *Important:* Gas produced is very toxic. Ensure adequate ventilation; do not breathe the vapors.
  - Crush sal ammoniac finely. Place an even layer (no more than 2 cm thick) in a Pyrex dish; cover with the glass cover.
  - Heat until sublimation occurs (sal ammoniac sublimates at 520°C). Sublimate deposits ~1 inch thick on the bottom of the lid.
  - Scrape off sublimate; sublime again. Repeat until there is no black residue and all the salt sublimes. *Triple sublimation is required.* If the salt is yellow after sublimation, that is a good sign. This triple-sublimed sal ammoniac is used throughout the mineral work.
]


