==== Chapter 12: The Herbal Work

- Mercury (Spirit = Alcohol), Sulphur (Soul = Essential Oil), and Salt (Body = Mineral Salts) are three interpenetrating matrices — each dependent on the others in creating and maintaining the plant.
- *Mercury:* obtained through fermentation; same throughout the plant kingdom. *Sulphur:* obtained through distillation or pressing; unique to the particular species. *Salt:* obtained through calcination; made up of various mineral salts with potassium carbonate in the greatest proportion.
- Herbal work = separating, purifying, and recombining the Three Principles. This is called *spagyry, spagyria,* or *spagyrics* — from Greek *span* ("to tear open") and *ageirein* ("to collect," "to combine").
- A spagyric tincture differs from the usual herbal tincture in that the spagyric tinctures contain the plant *salts* that complete the full therapeutic profile of the plant.

===== Spagyric Tinctures (Two Methods)

#lab[
  *Method 1 (from dried herb):*
  1. Macerate herb in a 50:50 alcohol:water solution for two weeks. Use *aqua vitae* (50–60%) distilled from wine, or vodka. Filter; press the mass; save solution.
  2. Calcine the remaining vegetable solids to ash.
  3. Option A: Add ash directly to the solution; circulate for a week; filter.
  4. Option B (more refined): Extract and purify the Salt of Tartar from the ash; then add this purified salt to the tincture.

  *Method 2 (fresh herb, fermentation-based — after John French, Art of Distillation):*
  1. Chop fresh herb; add water, yeast, and sugar (optional). Set to ferment until no more gas is produced.
  2. Using an aludel, distill very gently until there are two parts distillate for every one part of fresh herb used.
  3. Add enough pure Mercury (95%+ alcohol) to bring the concentration to at least 15%.
  4. Calcine the remaining vegetable matter. Purify the salts; add to the tincture.
]

- Tinctures should be made for each of the seven planets.

===== The Herbal Magistry

#lab[
  - A Magistry = the *medicinal virtue of a substance preserved in a vehicle* — all the virtues of the plant, purified and intensified. 1:1 by weight:volume (500 g dried herb : 500 ml solvent).
  1. Macerate 0.5 kg herb in 2 liters water for 1–3 days. Add more water to bring volume to 2 liters. Distill off the essential oil (Sulphur); separate and keep in dark glass. Letting the flask rest 12–24 hours, then resuming, extracts more Sulphur.
  2. Adjust remaining mixture to 27°C; add yeast starter and sugar; let ferment until complete. Strain; set mass aside for calcination. Distill out the Spirit (Mercury); rectify; keep in glass bottle.
  3. Calcine the remaining liquid (evaporate first) and solids to ash together. Dissolve, filter, evaporate repeatedly until salts are as pure as possible. This is the Salt.
  4. Mix 500 ml Mercury + all the Sulphur + all the Salt. Add enough Mercury to dissolve the Salts; then add all the Sulphur. Add more Mercury if needed to keep everything in solution. Seal; digest 1 month at 40°C; circulate for an additional month. Add more Mercury if necessary. This is the Magistry.
  - Magisteries for each of the seven planets should be made.
]

===== The Spagyric Plant Stone (Vegetable Stone)

#lab[
  - Combine Salt + Sulphur + Mercury so that Salt and Sulphur predominate → produces a hard wax-like substance (Vegetable Stone). Has all the virtues of the plant in greatly intensified form.

  *Preferred order of combination:*
  1. Salt should be very well calcined and heated for 1 hour before use (to drive off all water — oil and water do not mix). Place hot Salt evenly in a flask; add Sulphur to cover the Salt in slight excess. Seal; incubate at 40°C for 1 week. When the amount of Sulphur floating on top equals what was added, the Salt has absorbed all it can — it will have a waxy, slimy appearance.
  2. Add enough Mercury to cover the Salt/Sulphur mixture in slight excess. Digest; add more Mercury until the Salt cannot absorb any more.
  3. *Alternative (equal mixture method):* Mix 1 part Mercury + 1 part Sulphur; add this to purified Salt so that a thin layer (1 cm) floats above the Salt. Digest and circulate 1 week. Repeat until the Salt melts like wax during calcination without smoking.
  4. *Test:* Place a piece in water. If it dissolves, use a higher proportion of Sulphur to Mercury and cycle through more calcinations and imbibitions. It is the Sulphur that holds the Stone together — the Soul allowing union of Spirit and Body.
  5. Digest in incubator for 6 months to 1 year until solid. This is the Vegetable Stone.

  *For plants with little or no volatile oil:*
  - Macerate plant in Rectified Spirit of Wine. Distill off the Mercury (determined through intimate contact with the plant — save for recombination). Add distilled water to remaining greenish liquid; digest in water bath at ~80°C until the water becomes very intense red. Cool; filter. Evaporate very slowly → crystallizes or forms a honey-like syrup. Dissolve and recrystallize to purify (Salt of Sulphur). Mix with Salt; imbibe with determined Mercury; follow above procedures.
]

===== Primum Ens Melissae

- *Primum ens* = the first matter; seat of life and motion. The *ens* is the essential healing aspect of a plant — its virtue.

#doctrine[
  Report by Lesebure, physician of Louis XIV (from Franz Hartman's biography of Paracelsus): A physician took the primum ens Melissae every morning at sunrise in a glass of white wine for fourteen days. His finger- and toe-nails began to fall out without pain. He gave the remedy to an old female servant (unknowingly); after about ten days she began to menstruate again as in former days. He then soaked grain in the wine and gave it to an old hen — on the sixth day the bird began to lose its feathers. Before two weeks had passed, new feathers grew, much more beautifully colored; her comb stood up again, and she began again to lay eggs.
]

#lab[
  - *This procedure can be used to extract the ens from any herb* — particularly useful for plants with little essential oil.
  1. Cover fresh Lemon Balm (*Melissa officinalis*) leaves with Oil of Tartar. Seal and digest. In 24–48 hours, the Oil of Tartar extracts a tincture. Draw off the tincture; discard the leaves.
  2. Pour very sharp Mercury (Rectified Spirit of Wine) on top so it covers the liquid 2–5 cm deep. When it becomes intensely tinged, remove and save it; put fresh Mercury on. Repeat until all color is absorbed. May take 1–3 months.
  3. Gently distill the combined tinged alcohol until the tincture in the flask begins to thicken. Stop. Pour into an evaporation dish; allow remaining alcohol to evaporate until the thickness of syrup. This is the *primum ens Melissae*. (The distilled alcohol can be reused. Alternatively, the drawn-off tincture can be left as-is = Tincture of *primum ens Melissae*.)
  - Recommended low-Sulphur, friendly herbs for the seven planets:
    - Moon → Hyssop | Mercury → Savory | Venus → Lady's Mantle | Sun → Apothecary Rose | Mars → Basil | Jupiter → Lemon Balm | Saturn → Horsetail
]

===== Volatilized Salts of Tartar

- Central challenge: how to make the fixed (Salt of Tartar) become volatile. Three historical methods:

#lab[
  *Method 1 — Van Helmont (Ortus Medicinae, 1648):*
  Dissolve Salt of Tartar in warm wine vinegar; digest 40 days. Remove vinegar → clear crystalline salt remains. Dissolve in distilled rainwater; filter; evaporate → clear snow-white salt. Distill by water-bath a spirit; then let the remaining salt sit for another month in a sand bath → the salt will sublime and fix to the sides of the glass. This is the Volatilized Salt of Tartar.

  *Method 2 — Robert Boyle (1655):*
  Take Essential Oil (2 parts) + pure Salt of Tartar (1 part); circulate with bottom heat 3–4 months. The salt will be like sugar-candy, somewhat tincted by the oil, and will stick to the sides of the glass. [Stirke's modification: 3 parts oil, 2 parts salt.]

  *Method 3 — Dr. Geoffroy (via Encyclopedia Britannica, 1771):*
  Calcine Salt of Tartar; heat in crucible until red-hot; throw into a hot iron mortar and rub with a very hot iron pestle; as soon as powdered, pour on it little by little nearly an equal quantity of oil of turpentine. The oil enters and unites intimately with the salt to form a hard paste. Continue rubbing; as the turpentine disappears, add more until a softer consistency is obtained.

  *General principle:* To volatilize alkaline mineral salts, use organic acids — either acetic acid or the organic acids found in resins or volatile oils. Heat the salt first to ensure dryness; keep hot while adding the Sulphur.

  *Via distilled vinegar:* Add distilled vinegar to Salt of Tartar; it will effervesce. Keep adding until salt is saturated and fizzing stops. Place in flask; distill by sand bath very slowly to dryness. Add a little vinegar; saturate and distill to dryness again. Sublime the remaining solid. → *Volatile Salt of Tartar*.
]

===== The Circulatum Minus

- A *circulatum* is any medium or solvent that can be used and recovered to be used again. Source: Baro Urbigerus, short tract written 1691, giving very explicit directions for a *circulatum minus* — the lesser circulation. This circulatum quickly extracts the Three Principles from a fresh plant immersed in it. Within moments of immersion, the Sulphur, along with some of the Salt, begins to bubble up and float to the surface — concentrated, all the medicinal virtues of the immersed plant.
- The overall process: Sulphur is blended with Salt to volatilize it; more Sulphur added until Salt is saturated; this mixture is circulated with highly rectified Spirit of Wine and digested; then distilled and cohobated at least seven times; the final distillation yields the *circulatum minus*.

#lab[
  *Cotnoir's procedure based on Urbigerus Method III (from commercial materials):*

  *Materials for 500 ml of circulatum minus:*
  - ~20 g Salts (purified plant salts or calcined Salt of Tartar).
  - 25 ml Sulphur (steam-distilled essential oil of a plant).
  - 35 ml Balsam — best is copaiba or Italian pine (*Pinus pilaster* / oil of turpentine). Also workable: Canada balsam (*Abies balsamea*), Cypress, and others. *The resin must retain its naturally occurring organic acids* — these allow the Salt to volatilize. The Sulphur we refer to here is what Urbigerus calls the "sulphureous and bituminous Matter, issuing out of a plant" — a naturally occurring oleo-resin.
  - 500 ml Mercury (highly Rectified Spirit of Wine).

  *Process:*
  1. Moisten the Salt with the Sulphur until just wet. Then, little by little, add the balsam — grinding and mixing to a honey-like consistency at *40°C*. Use a mortar and pestle under a bell jar. Use all the Sulphur and all the Salts; then add a bit more resin. Consistency should be like honey.
  2. Digest the mixture at 40°C. When it becomes dry, re-imbibe with more resin. Stir frequently — 9–10 times a day. Exposure to air seems helpful in the volatilization of the Salt; do the work in a rather large stoppered (not fully sealed) flask. In *3–4 weeks*, the Salt should be fully saturated — slimy, glassy appearance, soapy to the touch. *This is the moment when the volatilization of the Salt takes place.*
  3. When the Salt is ready: add 8 parts of the rectified Mercury to 1 part of the Salt/Sulphur/balsam mixture. Let the mix putrefy for 8–10 days, stirring daily. Notice a color change; the Salt will appear like slime at the bottom of the flask. Circulate for 1 week.
  4. Distill carefully — *do not let the resin come over or allow it to burn.* Cohobate (pour the distillate back over the remaining mixture). Additional digestions may be useful. Repeat this cycle of distillation and cohobation a *total of seven times*. Then do the final distillation.
  5. The distillate has a very sharp odor. It is the *circulatum minus*.

  *Test:* Immerse a few leaves from a fresh plant. A proper circulatum will separate out the Three Principles in less than fifteen minutes.

  Note: This process is very simple but rather tricky. Be prepared for several attempts before succeeding. Even in failure, experience is gained. Even if the distillate is not the *circulatum minus*, it is still a wonderful and refined spagyric tincture.
]


