=== Appendix One: Technique and Equipment

==== Laboratory Safety (18 Points)

Two general rules: *Know the theory before attempting the practice.* *When in doubt, do not do it.*

1. Prepare in depth before starting. 2. Know the properties of the substances (consult *The Merck Index* or *CRC of Chemistry and Physics*). 3. Never mix substances "just to see what happens." 4. Safety or prescription glasses at all times (contact lenses are inadequate). 5. Adequate footwear; long hair confined; gloves when working with acids, bases, or substances absorbable through skin (e.g. antimony). 6. Never eat, drink, or smoke in the lab. 7. To note odors, waft to your nose with your hand — do not stick your nose over it and sniff. 8. When diluting acids or bases, always add acid or base to the water. 9. Use a towel when inserting or removing glass tubing or thermometers into rubber stoppers; use water to lubricate rubber. 10. Never heat flammable liquids with an open flame, or when any open flame is near. 11. Check and recheck all connections of a setup. 12. Always keep a charged all-purpose fire extinguisher handy. 13. Always have a source of fresh cold running water available; slightly warm water preferred for eye flushing. Have a first aid kit available. 14. Be careful with hot glassware and metal rings. 15. Label things clearly with indelible ink. 16. Keep the laboratory or workplace well ventilated at all times. 17. Do not work on days when in a bad mood, not feeling well, or becoming fatigued — months of work could be lost in seconds due to one small accident. 18. Think and use your common sense.

==== Equipment List

_For distillation:_ Flasks, adapters, condensors, thermometer, oil separator, aludel, clamps, stands, rubber tubing, electric heat source. _For calcination:_ Stainless steel pans, ceramic casserole dishes, screens, crucibles. _For measurement:_ Scales (mass), graduated cylinders (volume), thermometers (temperature), hydrometer (liquid density), pH paper (acidity). _Heat sources:_ Sun, dung, incubator, hot plate, heating mantle, Bunsen burner, stove, oven, open charcoal fire. _Miscellaneous:_ Beakers, funnels, filter paper, mortar and pestle, glass stirring rods, clamps and stands, silicon stopcock grease, glass jars, bottles, and jugs, cleaning supplies. _Safety:_ Gloves, fire extinguisher, eye protection, proper disposal system, first aid kit.

==== Distillation Setup

- *Ground glass-jointed equipment:* Round distilling flask, vacuum adapter, distilling head, round bottom flask, thermometer adapter, clamps, stands, thermometer, condenser and tubes, heat source.
- *Standard glassware equipment:* Distilling flask + one-holed rubber stopper (for thermometer) or two-holed stopper (thermometer + bent glass tube), thermometer, receiving flask, heat source, condenser with hoses and one-holed rubber stopper, clamps and stands.
- Heat source must be electric hot plate or heating mantle when distilling alcohol or other flammables.


=== Appendix Two: Plants and Planets

Three systems for determining planetary rulership: (1) *The Mythic* — plants as related to gods of Greek and Roman mythology. (2) *The Functional* — the effects plants have on the body and the planetary rulership of the part affected. (3) *The Doctrine of Signatures* — form, color, and/or habitat of the plant as related to the planets. Drawn from Nicholas Culpeper and William Lilly (1602–1681). Not to be followed slavishly, but with thought and consideration as to the ultimate use of the plant.

